english:
  title: On the Eighteenth Day of the Ninth Month, Setting Out at Dawn to Meet the Regional Commander at Angok Station—A Gift Poem for Jeong Gangsu
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Through the blare of military horns I tighten saddle and bridle,
    Rushing to receive the commander's banners—the station-house seems far.
    Ten leagues through the rough village and torches pierce the cottages,
    The waning moon at fifth watch, frost gathering thick in my boots.
    Hunting rabbits, striking foxes—such sport delights the soul,
    Planting pines, questioning the bamboo—is this not a man's home?
    Beyond the creek the frost-bearded elder feels ashamed,
    Awakened from his sweet dreams of snores by the dawn pipes' call.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'regional commander' (節度使) refers to a high-ranking provincial official, here arriving for inspection.
  - key: ''
    value: Fifth watch refers to the hours just before dawn in traditional Korean timekeeping.
  - key: ''
    value: The images of hunting and planting suggest both the active pursuits of an official and the peaceful life of a hermit—a tension at the heart of the poem.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'frost-bearded elder' likely refers to the poet himself or a companion, contrasting the urgency of official duties with the desire for simple, undisturbed rest.
